                            <comment id="13397492" author="hustlmsp" created="Wed, 20 Jun 2012 14:28:15 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;attach a patch to fix this issue, which includes a test case reproduce the problem.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;this fix is quite simple, just carrying &lt;b&gt;numMessagesRead&lt;/b&gt; and &lt;b&gt;totalSizeRead&lt;/b&gt; to next scanMessages call to avoid scanning too much messages.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13403194" author="ikelly" created="Thu, 28 Jun 2012 17:19:36 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Fix is good +1. Committing.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13403198" author="ikelly" created="Thu, 28 Jun 2012 17:24:23 +0100"  >&lt;p&gt;Just to summarize, due to the changes in &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/BOOKKEEPER-49&quot; title=&quot;bookkeeper - parallel async read same entry of same ledger will fail&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;BOOKKEEPER-49&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;BOOKKEEPER-49&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, the numMessagesRead was not being passed between subsequent calls to read entries (which occurred when ledgers changed). This resulted in some requests reading too many entries, which could interfere(&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/BOOKKEEPER-49&quot; title=&quot;bookkeeper - parallel async read same entry of same ledger will fail&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;BOOKKEEPER-49&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;BOOKKEEPER-49&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;) with later reads from the persistence manager.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
